metadata.name: Outside your Window #32
metadata.description:
Never take for granted that we sit in the safety of our homes, behind our windows, sheltered from the elements outside. 

The characteristics of the rain outside the window, and the window itself, will be determined by the mint hash. However, the background color of this piece will constantly change based on the hour of day it is loaded, hence note that the thumbnail will only technically be accurate 1/24 hours out of the day as it represents a static snapshot taken at the time of token rendering.

100% of the primary proceeds will be donated towards flood relief efforts for the devastating December 2021 floods in Malaysia.

Made in p5js
Created December 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: CONNECT D-ajop1j021 #16
metadata.description:
※Due to the characteristics of the work, the output will vary depending on the screen size.
If the screen size is the same, the output will be the same.
Thumbnail images are 800px x 800px.

First, the base color is placed, then random symbols (letters) are placed in a draw() loop process.
Then, specific symbol are linked to each other by their x,y color.

Red, Blue, Yellow, and Black colors are references to the untitled print work by Hiroshi Kawano, and works by Mondrian. I started this work by imitating and looking at their work.

This work is the beginning of my exploration of the relationship between weaving, computers, and generation, and I plan to produce the CONNECT series using similar techniques.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js

metadata.name: The Distant peaks #103
metadata.description:
The Distant Peaks is the first generative art release that combines my collection on Objkt:
"The Windless Summit and The Distant sea"

Since the beginning, I want to create a plotter printer or generative art style. but I don't have the basic knowledge to do creative coding, so I tried to replicate it with The Help of artificial intelligence and now I'm collaborating with @rosetta196 to help me experiment with the generative art area.

Each piece in this collection is a unique and intricate representation of the rugged peaks and sweeping vistas of mountains, as well as the calming of the ocean's waves. The colors, textures, and movements of the artwork are all meticulously crafted through code, with every detail carefully considered to capture the essence of these natural wonders.

The use of pure code to generate these landscapes serves to highlight the beauty and complexity of mathematics and computer programming. 
It is a testament to the power of technology and its ability to create stunning works of art that evoke deep emotions and inspire creativity.

As you gaze upon the art, you are drawn into a world of tranquility and natural beauty. The peacefulness of the mountains and the endless expanse of the ocean come to life, inviting you to explore and discover the wonders of the natural world. 
This art project is a celebration of the beauty of nature and the incredible potential of generative art.


by Samanta and Rosetta196 2023

metadata.name: Floating Medusas #60
metadata.description:
Floating Medusas is a generative piece. A group of little creatures creating an organic visual. 

The size, position and frequency of creatures are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Each creature is masking by a geometric pattern. Creatures have straight or smooth edges.
The shapes’s sizes of the patterns are visible as features, like the edge’s type and the number of creatures.  

Handmade by code with javascript, made with fragment.tools 
Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2022

metadata.name: Departure Within Shattered Windmills #175
metadata.description:
I wrote the following when reviewing the outputs...

The wind is gone,
My windmill falls,
I reach out to catch the pieces.
Half fall in my right hand,
The others in my left,
Two stacks of colored paper.
I’m holding my windmill,
I feel the breeze in my hair.
Each hand is empty,
My windmill rises,
I can see the wind.

'Departure Within Shattered Windmills' was originally inspired by suprematism, and then started to gain more complexity. It is still a combination of simple features, subdivided quads drawn on different planes of perspective. Chaos simulated by many organized grids. Countless pieces of a windmill.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #660
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: AERO #189
metadata.description:
AERO

In the stillness of the void, floating cities hang suspended, bound by no earthly gravity. The buildings, wrought in shades of dreamy pastels, appear as though they have been plucked from some other time and place, and set adrift in a new and unknowable realm.

Here, amidst the stillness and silence, ropes hang loosely like vines, connecting the structures in a delicate web of possibility. The architecture of the buildings is vaguely familiar, yet strangely surreal, hinting at a past now forgotten.

As the eye wanders through this landscape of suspended structures, a feeling of nostalgia begins to seep in. There is a sense that these cities were once inhabited, bustling with the energy of human life. Now, they stand alone, abandoned and forgotten, as nature slowly reclaims its territory.



The AERO series explores how a minimalistic set of shapes and rules can be extrapolated to create complex assemblies, the same way individual buildings will form villages and cities.

To add a sense of organic texture to these geometric structures, ropes that connect certain squares have been added. They can sometimes take on the appearance of vines. This addition aims creates a sense of tension between the man-made and the natural.



Double click or double tap to save the current image

In fullscreen mode / live view:
Add "&size=xxxx" at the end of the url to generate a custom sized image
Add "&clean" at the end of the url to remove the grain effect


Artist: Estienne
Feb. 2023
